---

import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro"
import TopLayout from "@layouts/TopLayout.astro"
import BottomLayout from "@layouts/BottomLayout.astro"
import { RESEARCH } from "@consts"
---

<PageLayout title={RESEARCH.TITLE} description={RESEARCH.DESCRIPTION}>
  <TopLayout>
    <div class="animate">
      <h1 class="text-highlight-light text-5xl md:text-6xl font-extrabold">
        Research
      </h1>

  <div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-widest mt-3 opacity-75">
    MASTER'S THESIS • NEUSTEM LAB • UNIVERSITY OF MIAMI
  </div>

<p class="text-lg mt-6 max-w-3xl">
  My master's thesis research focused on
  <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
    Schwann cell-nanoparticle interactions
  </span>
  in neural lesion models, with an emphasis on biomaterial design,
  cellular uptake, and applications in
  <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
    spinal cord injury
  </span>
  research. Research findings were presented at the University of Miami College of Engineering Research Symposium (Oct. 2025), the Biomedical Engineering Master's Symposium (Dec. 2025), and Neuroscience Research Day at the Miller School of Medicine.
</p>
</div>

  </TopLayout>

  <BottomLayout>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none animate">
      <section>
    <a
      href="/research/poster.png"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
    >
      <img
        src="/research/poster.png"
        alt="Master's thesis research poster"
        class="rounded-xl border border-black/10 dark:border-white/25 shadow-sm"
      />
    </a>
    <div class="text-sm italic mt-3 opacity-75">
      Figure 1. Research poster as presented at the 2025 University of Miami Neuroscience Research Day
    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2>Project Overview</h2>
    <p>
      This project investigates how engineered
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        nanoparticles (NPs)
      </span>
      interact with cells and biological
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        myelin debris
      </span>
      in lesion-like environments. The broader objective is to better understand how NP properties influence uptake, compatibility, and potential therapeutic delivery in nervous system injury models. Ultimately, this work seeks to provide insight into how nanoparticle-based therapies may be leveraged to promote neural repair and regeneration following injury.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2>Key Research Questions</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>How do Schwann cells interact with engineered nanoparticles?</li>
      <li>How does nanoparticle dose affect cellular uptake and viability?</li>
      <li>Can nanoparticle systems be studied alongside myelin debris in neural lesion models?</li>
      <li>How can biomaterial properties be tuned for regenerative medicine applications?</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2>Methods and Techniques</h2>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          Schwann cell culture
        </span>
        and cell maintenance
      </li>

      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          Nanoparticle synthesis
        </span>
        and characterization
      </li>

      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          Confocal microscopy
        </span>
        for uptake analysis
      </li>

      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          MTS, DMMB, and BCA assays
        </span>
      </li>

      <li>
          Mouse
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          brain harvest
        </span>
          and
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          hydraulic extrusion
        </span>
      </li>

      <li>
        <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
          Fiji/ImageJ
        </span>
        image processing
      </li>

      <li>
        Live Cell Imaging
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

<section class="mt-8">
  <h2>Research Outcomes</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      Demonstrated that
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        Schwann cells
      </span>
      showed minimal nanoparticle internalization following treatment, with observed nanoparticle accumulation occurring primarily around the cell membrane.
    </li>

    <li>
      Established that
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        blank nanoparticles (BNPs)
      </span>
      and
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        medium-molecular-weight chondroitin sulfate nanoparticles (MCS-NPs)
      </span>
      exhibited minimal cytotoxicity across a range of treatment conditions.
    </li>

    <li>
      Identified dose-dependent cytotoxic effects associated with
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        desulfated chondroitin sulfate nanoparticles (DCS-NPs)
      </span>
      during extended incubation studies.
    </li>

    <li>
      Developed and optimized protocols for
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        CNS myelin debris isolation
      </span>,
      competitive uptake experiments, and live-cell imaging of nanoparticle-cell interactions.
    </li>

    <li>
      Observed that
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        macrophages
      </span>
      readily internalized nanoparticles, while Schwann cells displayed distinct uptake behavior, suggesting cell-type-specific interactions with nanoparticle therapies.
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2>Research Significance</h2>

    <p>
      Spinal cord injury creates a complex lesion environment involving
      cellular stress, inflammatory signaling, myelin debris, and limited
      regenerative capacity. This research contributes to the development
      of biomaterial-based strategies that may support future approaches in
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        neural repair
      </span>,
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        drug delivery
      </span>,
      and
      <span class="font-semibold dark:font-bold dark:text-white">
        regenerative medicine
      </span>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-8">
    <h2>Additional Materials</h2>
    <p>
      For readers interested in a more detailed description of the project,
      methods, and results, the complete master's thesis is available below.
    </p>
    <p>
      <a
        href="/research/mastersthesis.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        class="font-semibold"
      >
        View Full Master's Thesis (PDF)
      </a>
    </p>
  </section>
</article>
  </BottomLayout>
</PageLayout>
